Blogger

Target IP: 192.168.194.217

Scanning



There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. Looks like HTTP is the enumeration entry-point.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Running whatweb on port 80 shows the host is using JQuery. It is running on Apache/2.4.18 Ubuntu machine.


The webpage above is displayed to us when we browse to this port. Right away, we get a hint with the name James; could this possibly be a username for SSH?


While running dirbuster, I managed to find a directory called /assets. This directory contains an interesting entry called /fonts/blog.


This blog application is running WordPress 4.9.8! The vhost name of this directory is called blogger.thm. I will append this inside the /etc/hosts file.


And now I have the pretty version of the WordPress website. This blog is about cybersecurity! Right away, I notice the username j@m3s. Performing a wpscan for usernames output this same username. Maybe we can bruteforce the password of this user?


Performing a gobuster search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.194.217/assets/fonts/blog/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt -x php,html,txt output the result above. This looks like a standard WordPress application. I tried to bruteforce the password of j@m3s but it did not work.


However, identifying the plugins was successful! The target machine is running a vulnerable plugin. The plugin wpdiscuz is vulnerable to RCE according to this exploit.

Exploitation


Looks like this GitHub repository contains the exploit code for this vulnerability. I downloaded this exploit on my machine and ran it against the WordPress application.




To exploit the machine, I noticed the web application allows image to be uploaded. I created a PHP PentestMonkey reverse shell. I added a magic bytes GIF89a; to bypass the filter and it worked. After firing up a listener on port 8443 and uploading the file, I got a reverse shell connection back on my listener port.

Privilege Escalation


Checking /etc/passwd shows an interesting user called vagrant. This username is quite popular in Linux. I was able to guess the password of this user by entering vagrant.


Looks like this user can run all commands as sudo. I exploited this weakness by spawning a new bash shell by entering the command sudo bash.
